<!--
Part A – Static Position
1.Create a webpage containing three boxes.
2.Apply position: static to the second box.
3.Try using top: 50px and left: 50px on the static box.
4.Observe and explain the result.

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Static Position</title>

    <style>
        .container {
            background-color: rgb(76, 131, 131);
            padding: 10px;
        }

        .box {
            height: 50px;
            width: 50px;
            margin: 10px;
            color: black;
            text-align: center;
            line-height: 50px;
        }

        .box1 {
            background-color: aquamarine;
        }

        .box2 {
            background-color: rgb(127, 140, 255);
            position: static;
            top: 50px;
            left: 50px;
        }

        .box3 {
            background-color: rgb(255, 127, 255);
        }
    </style>
</head>

<body>

    <div class="container">
        <div class="box box1">Box 1</div>
        <div class="box box2">Box 2</div>
        <div class="box box3">Box 3</div>
    </div>

    <h1>Observation and Explanation of Result</h1>

    <p>
        The second box has <code>position: static</code>. Even though
        <code>top: 50px</code> and <code>left: 50px</code> are applied,
        the box does not move from its original position.
    </p>

    <p>
        This happens because the default value of the position property is
        <code>static</code>. For static elements, the properties
        <code>top</code>, <code>right</code>, <code>bottom</code>, and
        <code>left</code> have no effect. The element remains in the normal
        document flow.
    </p>

</body>
</html>
